<H4><A NAME="SECTION00011020000000000000">
Graphs and Combinatorial Algorithms.</A>
</H4>

Part of our effort was devoted to studying dynamic path problems on
directed graphs.  We have introduced a general framework for casting
fully dynamic transitive closure into the problem of reevaluating
polynomials over matrices.  Using this technique, we have devised a
new deterministic algorithm that improves the best known bounds for
both fully-dynamic and deletion-only transitive closure on general
directed graphs.  Our algorithm maintains explicitly the transitive
closure as a Boolean matrix, supporting updates in <IMG
 WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="40" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$O(n^2)$"> amortized
time and queries in unit worst-case time.  We have also
proved that it is actually possible to break through the <IMG
 WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="40" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$O(n^2)$">
barrier on the single-operation complexity of fully dynamic
transitive
closure, solving a problem that has been open for many years. For the
problem of maintaining single-source shortest paths in a digraph with
<IMG
 WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="19" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img2.png"
 ALT="$n$"> vertices, <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="19" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$m$"> edges, and positive real edge weights, we have also
devised an algorithm that requires <!-- MATH
 $O(\sqrt{m} \log n)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="102" HEIGHT="38" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img4.png"
 ALT="$O(\sqrt{m} \log n)$"> worst-case
time in the <EM>output complexity</EM> per edge weight update. These
results appeared in&nbsp;[<A
 HREF="node9.html#ae-008">13</A>,<A
 HREF="node9.html#ae-015">15</A>].
